frameDefinitions: An Agent causes a Useful_location to become accessible (or non-accessible) to a Theme to a certain Degree.
An Obstruction blocks an Eclipsed entity partially or completely from view.

In this frame a Hindrance makes it more difficult for a Protagonist to complete their intended Action or a Hindrance directly affects an Action where the Action can be a natural act or the actions of many individuals in a collective endeavor.
A volitionally acting Interceptor takes control, without being authorized to do so by the sender, of a Theme that is underway from a sender to a recipient.

This frame involves a static (primarily spatial) relationship between a Location and a Theme, in which the Theme is located in many or all subregions of the Location, and is thus construable as covering it.
frameExamples: They've <t>blockaded</t> the entrance -- no one can get in or out.
A small green bulb <t>concealed</t> behind the panel flashed on momentarily .
Malcolm was <t>hindered</t> by his drinking problem .
Police <t>intercepted</t> the call and raided the address.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Useful_location</fen> is the place the <fen>Theme</fen> is headed towards and the <fen>Agent</fen> has changed the accessibility of.

The <fen>Agent</fen> may regulate access to the <fen>Useful_location</fen> by regulating access to a <fen>Portal</fen>, including a part of the portal that could block potential <fen>Theme</fen>s, such as doors or gates.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> changes the accessibility of the <fen>Useful_location</fen>.
The general <fen>Place</fen> where the blocking or allowing of access occurs.
The entity which blocks the <fen>Eclipsed</fen> entity from view.
The entity which is blocked from view.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the entity that tends towards or plans some <fen>Action</fen> which the <fen>Hindrance</fen> causes to be more difficult.
The <fen>Hindrance</fen> is the force which makes the <fen>Action</fen> more difficult or less likely to be successfully completed. The <fen>Hindrance</fen> may be a lack of enabling force:

The <fen>Action</fen> is what the <fen>Protagonist</fen> desires to do, which is made more difficult by the <fen>Hindrance</fen>. It can also be a natural act or collective endeavor, not linked to an overt <fen>Protagonist</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the <fen>Hindrance</fen> affects the <fen>Protagonist</fen> or <fen>Action</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> is the location where  he <fen>Hindrance</fen> affects the <fen>Protagonist</fen> or <fen>Action</fen>.
The volitional agent who without authorization of sender or recipient takes control of a <fen>Theme</fen> that is en route to a destination.
The entity, physical or abstract, construed as traveling from a sender to a goal location, which is taken hold of by the <fen>Interceptor</fen> without permission.
The time period during which the <fen>Interceptor</fen> takes control of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The location at which the <fen>Interceptor</fen> takes control of the <fen>Theme</fen>.

The <fen>Theme</fen> in this frame is the object which is described as standing in some spatial relation to a particular <fen>Location</fen>.  <fen>Theme</fen> typically occurs as the External Argument or, with passives, as a PP Complement headed by 'with' or 'by'.
<fen>Location</fen> is the entity or area with respect to which the <fen>Theme</fen>'s spatial arrangement is described.  This frame element generally occurs as an NP Object.
The time at which the <fen>Theme</fen> occupies the <fen>Location</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Police</fex> have cordoned off the area where the crime took place.
Protestors barricaded <fex>a highway that connects the industrial sectors to the ports</fex>.
They've blockaded <fex>the entrance</fex> -- no one can get in or out.
A rebel group blockaded the roadways <fex>late last night</fex>.
Many roads were cordorned off <fex>in the central district</fex> right after the incident.
The mists obscured <fex>the top of the tower</fex>.
The project was hampered <fex>by a lack of funds</fex>.
Two days later, <fex>an aerial patrol</fex> intercepted an enemy trying the same thing.
They could either sail west down the Channel or north-east to intercept <fex>an enemy making for the Thames estuary</fex>.
The five had been intercepted <fex>after a DFLP attack on March 5</fex>.
She had been intercepted <fex>outside Guy 's room</fex> and would be severely punished.
